Subject: [PATCH] webgpu: correct sampler binding types for lit and shadowed 3D

Patch 0013 made a simple unshaded 3D scene render, but any scene with real
materials, lighting, or shadows still produced a black frame. Two further
defects, both in how the driver describes samplers to WebGPU:

1. Over-eager "unused" classification. 0013 marked a sampler/texture binding
   unused (visibility None) unless its WGSL variable appeared inside a texture
   builtin. Godot's lighting and PCF helpers take the texture as a FUNCTION
   PARAMETER, so the global's name never appears in a builtin call and the
   binding was wrongly demoted -> "Entry point's stage (Fragment) is not in the
   binding visibility in the layout (ShaderStage::None)" and every scene
   pipeline was rejected. The vertex stage keeps the strict builtin test (that
   is what buys back the 16-samplers-per-stage headroom 0013 exists for), while
   fragment/compute now count a binding as used when its variable is referenced
   anywhere beyond its own declaration, which covers helper-function passing.

2. Depth textures paired with filtering samplers. WebGPU requires a
   Depth-sample-type texture to be used with a NonFiltering or Comparison
   sampler, but the BGL declared plain Filtering, so Dawn rejected the scene
   pipeline: "Texture binding is TextureSampleType::Depth but used statically
   with a sampler that's SamplerBindingType::Filtering". Godot reads the scene
   depth buffer and shadow maps exactly this way. The WGSL is now scanned for
   non-comparison texture builtins that pair a depth texture with a sampler, and
   those sampler layout entries are declared NonFiltering. Because Godot still
   supplies its own (linear) sampler for those slots, the driver also creates a
   nearest/non-filtering sampler and substitutes it wherever a layout entry
   demands one -- in uniform_set_create for both plain and combined
   sampler+texture bindings, and in the bind-group adaptation path.

Verified on an NVIDIA Tesla P40 (Vulkan) through headed Chrome/WebGPU: a scene
with six PBR meshes, a directional light and real-time shadow mapping renders
correctly at 59-60 fps, 36 draws per frame, with 0 GPUValidationError (was 2283
before 0013, and still 1980 with 0013 alone). Shadows, specular response, and
depth-buffer reads all behave.

